{
  "doc_id": "39023",
  "text": "The anatomical and functional organization of the central auditory pathway in songbirds largely resembles that found in other vertebrates, including mammals ( Fig. 1) [CITATION_1] . Auditory input is transduced in the cochlea, ascends through brainstem areas analogous to mammalian cochlear nuclei, and arrives at the dorsal lateral mesencephalic nucleus (MLd), the avian homolog of the mammalian inferior colliculus, or auditory midbrain [CITATION_2] . MLd neurons send direct projections to the thalamic nucleus Ovoidalis (Ov), the avian homolog of the ventral medial geniculate [CITATION_3] . Both structures participate in auditory discrimination and are tuned to behaviorally relevant signals [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . Ov projects to a pronounced lobe in the forebrain that contains auditory areas (Fig. 1) . Inside this lobe, the caudomedial nidopallium (NCM) receives input from the thalamo-recipient Field L and is heavily interconnected with the caudomedial mesopallium (CMM). NCM and CMM are analogous to the supragranular layers of mammalian auditory cortex [CITATION_7] or to mammalian auditory association cortex [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] . In this study, we quantified soundinduced CA activity both immunohistochemically and via HPLC at multiple levels of this pathway [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] .",
